Heteroatom anchors Fe-Mn dual-atom catalysts with bi-functional oxygen catalytic activity for low-temperature rechargeable flexible Zn-air batteries Yuting He 1 Hongtao Li 1 Yi Wang Yufei Jia Yongning Liu Qiang Tan ⁎ State Key Laboratory for Mechanical Behaviour of Materials, School of Materials Science & Engineering, Xi'an Jiaotong University, Xi'an 710049, Shaanxi, China State Key Laboratory for Mechanical Behaviour of Materials School of Materials Science & Engineering Xi'an Jiaotong University Xi'an Shaanxi 710049 China State Key Laboratory for Mechanical Behaviour of Materials, School of Materials Science & Engineering, Xi'an Jiaotong University, Xi'an, Shaanxi 710049, China ⁎ Corresponding author. 1 These authors contributed equally to this work. Graphical abstract Dual-atom catalyst exhibits outstanding activity lies in the amount of site density, which is more than that of single-atom catalysts. It owns great potential in application of low-temperature Zn-air batteries. M−N−C (M = Fe, Co, Ni, etc.) catalyst owns high catalytic activity in the oxygen catalytic reaction which is the most likely to replace the Pt-based catalysts. But it is still a challenge to further increase the active site density. This article constructs the high-efficiency FeMn-N/S-C-1000 catalyst to realize ORR/OER bifunctional catalysis by hetero-atom, bimetal (Fe, Mn) doped simultaneously strategy. When evaluated it as bi-functional electro-catalysts, FeMn-N/S-C-1000 exhibits excellent catalytic activity (E 1/2 = 0.924 V, Ej =10 = 1.617 V) in alkaline media, outperforms conventional Pt/C, RuO2 and most non-precious-metal catalysts reported recently. Such outstanding performance is owing to N, S co-coordinated with metal to form multi-types of single atom, dual atom active sites to carry out bi-catalysis. Importantly, nitrite poison test provides the proof that the active sites of FeMn-N/S-C are more than that of single-atom catalysts to promote catalytic reactions directly. To better understand the local structure of Fe and Mn active sites, XAS and DFT were employed to reveal that FeMn-N5/S-C site plays the key role during catalysis. Notably, the FeMn-N/S-C-1000 based low-temperature rechargeable flexible Zn-air also exhibits superior discharge performance and extraordinary durability at −40 °C. This work will provide a new idea to design diatomic catalysts applied in low-temperature rechargeable batteries. Keywords FeMn-N/S-C-1000 ORR OER Rechargeable flexible Zn-air batteries 1 Introduction Green renewable energy storage devices, such as rechargeable metal (zinc, lithium, etc.) air batteries, are attracting more and more attention because they can avoid environmental degradation caused by the burning of fossil fuels [1–6]. However, sluggish kinetics of oxygen cathode seriously restricts the application of rechargeable metal-air batteries [7–13]. A common consensus for improving battery performance is developing high-activity, and low-cost catalysts. Traditional Pt-group metal (PGM) catalysts based metal-air batteries are difficult to be commercialized due to the scarcity of resources and high cost [14–16]. So it is urgent to study transition metal catalysts to replace PGM catalysts. M−N−C (M = Fe, Co, Ni, etc.) single-atom catalyst is one of the most developed catalysts with better performance than PGM catalysts [17–22]. Its excellent activity, controllable structure and variety active sites are favor to researchers. However, how to prepare catalysts owning intrinsic activity density, large specific surface area and multi-functionality is still a great challenge. Heteroatoms (B, P, S, and N) doping of the carbon matrix can modulate the electronic structure to promote oxygen catalysis, which has been proved by many studies [23–29]. Among these studies, the sulfur exhibits an obvious doping effect on Fe-N-C families to improve the catalytic activity than other heteroatoms for great electronegativity [30–38]. What’s more, the introduction of another metal is essential to stabilize the single active site and to increase the site density (SD) of the metal. As a result, the constructed diatom site can realize multi-functional (such as ORR, OER, etc.) and efficient catalysis [39–50]. Many studies [51–54] have proved that the increase of SD can directly affect the catalytic activity of catalyst. However, quantification of active sites by in situ electrochemical method remains elusive. Kucernak [55] and colleagues developed an electrochemical method to quantify the SD of Fe-N-C by nitrite adsorption followed by stripping. Specifically, the nitrite ion (NO2 −) first interacts strongly with the metal center, selectively poisoning the catalytic center of the Fe atom, rather than the carrier material. The activity of the catalyst is recovered by electrochemical removal of nitrite ions, resulting in a measurable charge transfer signal, which can be used to estimate the number of stripping charge and thus calculate how many active sites there are. Hereinto, we developed the two strategies of hetero-atomic doping and bimetallic Fe and Mn co-doped to prepare a bi-functional catalyst which catalyzes ORR and OER simultaneously. The preparation method is the same as that in the previous paper [34], which achieved the catalyst via a facile micellar template strategy. It is greatly inspired the abundant nitrogen polymer PANI as the raw materials. With the SDS soft template modified to construct the S doped, higher specific area catalyst. Differently, Fe and Mn metals are adsorbed to construct high-performance N, S co-doped diatom catalysts. The coordination structure of active (Fe-N x , Mn-N x ) moieties have been dramatically transformed by the doped heteroatom S. The best diatomic FeMn-N/S-C-1000 owns a positive half-wave potential (E 1/2 = 0.924 V vs. RHE), which is superior to benchmark commercial Pt/C (E 1/2 = 0.867 V vs. RHE) in both catalytic activity and stability. A potential at 10 mA cm−2 (Ej =10 = 1.617 V vs. RHE) as OER performance is a bit more negative than that of the benchmark RuO2 (Ej =10 = 1.533 V vs. RHE), but its stability is comparable to RuO2. The qualification of actives sites of FeMn-N/S-C-1000 is evaluated by nitrite poisoning, in which FeMn-N/S-C-1000 owns more sites (9.169 × 1018 sites g−1) to exhibit excellent performance than that of single-atom catalysts. When FeMn-N/S-C-1000 assembled as cathode catalyst in the aqueous and flexible Zn-air battery, it exhibited a high power density and remarkable durability at both ambient and even sub-zero temperatures (down to −40 °C). In order to apply FeMn-N/S-C-1000 in extremely harsh condition, low-temperature flexible rechargeable ZABs of FeMn-N/S-C-1000 (Fig. 6f) is also carried out. The FeMn-N/S-C-1000 based rechargeable ZABs can work normally at. It can output such higher power density of 47.9 and 16.3 mW cm−2 at −20 and −40 °C (Fig. 6g) respectively, which is superior to other catalysts listed in Table S15. Notably, the discharge recovery at different current density of the battery at low temperature is also excellent shown in Fig. 6(h). To further reveal its strong stability, a 170 h charge–discharge cycle test was performed at the current density of 2 mA cm−2 (Fig. 6i), suggesting FeMn-N/S-C-1000 displays a long-lasting durability of at −40 °C. This result provides a new application of FeMn-N/S-C-1000 at low-temperature condition. 4 Conclusions To sum up, the dual-atom FeMn-N/S-C catalyst was successfully synthesized by Fe,Mn two atoms anchored in carbon matrix via a facile micellar template strategy and modified polymer pyrolysis route. With the N,S co-doped the structure to form abundant active sites and assistance of the Fe,Mn dual-atom interaction, the active site density and the intrinsic activity has been dramatically enhanced than the single atom catalyst. The optimized FeMn-N/S-C-1000 exhibits bi-functional outstanding catalytic activity (E 1/2 = 0.924 V, Ej =10 = 1.617 V) and superior long-term durability for ORR/OER. XAS and DFT proved the nature of the excellent bi-functional electro-catalysis is owing to the dual-atom site. Its excellent performance is owing to some reasons. (i) The higher surface area of FeMn-N/S-C-1000 can load more active sites. Besides, its micropore-mesopore structure is easier to adsorb O2 easily and to realize fast mass transfer channel to accelerate ORR and OER. (ii) The N,S atoms doped in the matrix can form multi-types active sites and regulate electron structure of Fe,Mn metals to accelerate the catalytic reactions. More importantly, the vital FeMn-N5/S-C diatomic site owns significantly higher density of states to promote the electron transfer. It greatly lowers the energy barrier of RLS to enhance ORR and OER activity. (iii) Nitrite poisoned method tests the SD of the Mn-N/S-C-1000, Fe-N/S-C-1000 and FeMn-N/S-C-1000 were calculated as 5.423 × 1018, 5.782 × 1018 and 9.169 × 1018 sites g−1, respectively. It proves FeMn-N/S-C-1000 owns the most active sites density to promote the catalysis. When applied it on aqueous, flexible rechargeable ZABs, the FeMn-N/S-C catalyst exhibits outstanding output performance at room temperature and −40 °C low-temperature. This work provides a new idea to design diatomic catalysts applied in low temperature rechargeable batteries. coredata.dc:description: M−N−C (M = Fe, Co, Ni, etc.) catalyst owns high catalytic activity in the oxygen catalytic reaction which is the most likely to replace the Pt-based catalysts. But it is still a challenge to further increase the active site density. This article constructs the high-efficiency FeMn-N/S-C-1000 catalyst to realize ORR/OER bifunctional catalysis by hetero-atom, bimetal (Fe, Mn) doped simultaneously strategy. When evaluated it as bi-functional electro-catalysts, FeMn-N/S-C-1000 exhibits excellent catalytic activity (E 1/2 = 0.924 V, Ej =10 = 1.617 V) in alkaline media, outperforms conventional Pt/C, RuO2 and most non-precious-metal catalysts reported recently. Such outstanding performance is owing to N, S co-coordinated with metal to form multi-types of single atom, dual atom active sites to carry out bi-catalysis. Importantly, nitrite poison test provides the proof that the active sites of FeMn-N/S-C are more than that of single-atom catalysts to promote catalytic reactions directly. To better understand the local structure of Fe and Mn active sites, XAS and DFT were employed to reveal that FeMn-N5/S-C site plays the key role during catalysis. Notably, the FeMn-N/S-C-1000 based low-temperature rechargeable flexible Zn-air also exhibits superior discharge performance and extraordinary durability at −40 °C. This work will provide a new idea to design diatomic catalysts applied in low-temperature rechargeable batteries.
